{{more footnotes|date=September 2014}} {{redirects here|LOTE|other uses|Lote (disambiguation)}} '''LOTE''' or '''Languages Other Than English''' is the name given to language subjects, other than English, at [[Australian]], [[New York City|New York]], and other schools. The name evolved from '[[heritage language]]', a term first used to refer to languages other than French and English in Canada. Later modified in relation to Australia to refer to languages other than English.<ref>{{cite web|last1=King|first1=Kendall A.|last2=Ennser-Kananen|first2=Johanna|title=Heritage Languages and Language Policy|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/277698847_Heritage_Languages_and_Language_Policy|accessdate=July 1, 2016|doi=10.1002/9781405198431.wbeal0500|date=5 November 2012}}</ref> LOTEs have often historically been related to the policy of [[multiculturalism]], and tend to reflect the predominant non-English languages spoken in a school's local area, the idea being to play a part in the maintenance of cultural identities in local communities.{{cn|date=June 2016}}
'''LOTE''' is also used to describe written material presented in languages other than English.<ref name="ala">{{cite web|title=Cultivating Non-English Collections: a unique partnership that alleviates the pain of librarians in multi-language communities {{!}} Offices of the American Library Association|url=http://www.ala.org/offices/iro/iroactivities/cultivatingnonenglish|website=www.ala.org|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> == LOTE in Australia == '''LOTE''' is becoming an increasingly popular subject in Australian Schools. The Draft Shape of the Australian Curriculum: Languages, produced by ACARA, has suggested three tiers of languages to be taught in Australian schools: {| class="wikitable" |- ! Tier 1 !! Tier 2 !! Tier 3 |- | [[Italian language|Italian]] || [[Japanese language|Japanese]] || [[Standard Arabic|Arabic]] |- | [[Standard Chinese|Chinese]] || [[French language|French]] || [[Greek language|Modern Greek]] |- | || [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] || [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]] |- | || [[Korean language|Korean]] || |- | || [[Hindi]] || |- | || [[Bengali language|Bengali]] || |- | || [[German language|German]] || |- | || [[Spanish language|Spanish]] || |}
Tier 1 languages were chosen because they cater for the needs of the greatest number of students. Italian is learnt by the most number of students and Chinese is a national priority.
Tier 2 languages were chosen because French, Japanese, Indonesian and German are some of the most frequently taught languages in Australian schools, Indonesian, Japanese and Korean are national priorities and Spanish "is a language of global importance".
Tier 3 languages were chosen because Arabic, Modern Greek and Vietnamese are the most frequently spoken foreign languages in Australian homes, and Arabic "is a language of global importance".
