{{refimprove|date=July 2010}}
The '''Universities Tests Act 1871'''<ref>[http://www.opsi.gov.uk/RevisedStatutes/Acts/ukpga/1871/cukpga_18710026_en_1 Universities Tests Act 1871], [[UK Government]].</ref> in the [[United Kingdom]] abolished the communion "Tests" and allowed Roman Catholics, non-conformists and non-Christians to take up [[fellow]]ships at the Universities of [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], [[University of London|London]] and [[University of Durham|Durham]].
Passed during the course of [[William Ewart Gladstone]]'s first ministry, the act was to obtain support from the non-conformists since these were a major support group for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}}
The direct instigation for this legislation was the widely publicised case of [[Numa Edward Hartog]], the first [[Jewish]] [[Senior Wrangler]] in the history of [[Cambridge University]], who could not accept the fellowship that would otherwise routinely be offered, because he could not [[Thirty-Nine Articles|subscribe to the required test]] on account of his religion. His testimony before the [[House of Lords]] helped secure passage of the bill, after the Lords had twice blocked similar legislation in 1869 and 1870.<ref>{{cite book|format=PDF|title=Quakers, Jews, and Science: Religious Responses to Modernity and the Sciences in Britain, 1650&ndash;1900|author=Geoffrey Cantor|authorlink=Geoffrey Cantor|publisher=Oxford University Press|date=2005|pages=85&ndash;87|isbn=0-19-927668-4}}</ref>
